fr.wl: I do not make any effort to meet FSMA compliance standards; if I did, I would probably go bankrupt.
cons.fr: Due to rules that create suboptimal outcomes, government conservation practices have proven to be inefficient and more costly, on a per-unit basis, than purely private solutions; the problem can add up to large percentages of the total costs, and can also lead to failure to implement contracts altogether (I say this from experience).
water.treat: No, we never treated our production water
fs.fr: I do not currently comply with FSMA.  I suspect that doing so would put profitability off to unachievable gross income levels.  I am at this time planning to try to continue under the radar as long as possible.
audit.fr: I assume that at least some legislators, technocrats and regulators may be well-meaning, but it is the results that count, and not their intentions.  Food safety regulations are increasingly killing off all hope of profitability for farm viability, except for the tiny hobby farms (exempt) and the incumbent big operations (%500,000+) who can bear the added costs, and they like the way these regs stifle their otherwise up-and-coming competition.  It is as though FSMA was purposely designed to achieve these results! But is anyone listening?  Food safety concerns are best addressed through the free market dynamics of robust tort law and the private insurance industry pressures that will flow from that.

fr.wl: Animal intrusion as a food safety issue is extremely overstated.  2 items that are often eaten raw at farmers markets by children and adults are snap peas and cherry tomatoes.  These are trellised and birds perch on them and shit all season long.  These crops are not washed crops for the vast majority of farmers.  People are eating bird shit on these crops all over the world all of the time.

cons.fr: We were using sequestered urine from composting toilets for fertilizer and were told by the state we couldn't sell any vegetables from that field. The composting toilets have conserved much water and energy (for pumping) and protected ground water. FSMA is making such conservation impossible, except on our own homestead food. It treats urine like biosolids, which is absurd since the urine doesn't pose the same threats as feces.

water.fr: We don't irrigate, but we spray.  We use potable water as the apple harvest approaches, but use untested surface water until then.  Agriculture already uses an unconscionable amount of water.  New food safety regulations are going to drive much of that use from surface water to ground water. The consequences of that to human and other life far outweigh any food safety gains.
